DIGEST
SB 388 Original 2026 Regular Session Hodges
Proposed law prohibits state agencies from awarding state contracts when the beneficiary
of the contract is a foreign adversaries, agent of foreign adversaries, foreign terrorist
organization, or agent of foreign terrorist organization. Proposed law gives the governor
emergency powers to cancel state contracts with foreign adversaries, agents of foreign
adversaries, foreign terrorist organizations, or agent of foreign terrorist organizations.
Proposed law provides for legislative declarations and findings as follows:
(1) If a state agency makes a contract and later learns that it benefits a foreign adversary
or a foreign terrorist organization, the contract is to be considered as providing
material aide, comfort, and support to the enemies of the people of La. and the
United States.
(2) It is the policy of the state that any contract that benefits a foreign adversary or a
foreign terrorist organization is subject to cancellation for cause as a threat to the
health and safety of the people of La. The cancellation is justified under the
reasonable exercise of the constitutional police powers of the state and is necessary
for the state to protect its people.
(3) Continuing any such contract poses a substantial risk to public safety, state security,
and the integrity of state government; therefore, it is imperative that the governor has
the emergency power to terminate such contracts for cause to protect the interest of
the state of La.
Proposed law defines "foreign adversary", "foreign terrorist organization", "state contract",
and "beneficiary of a contract".
Proposed law incorporates federal designations under 15 C.F.R. 791.4, 8 U.S.C. 1189, and
31 C.F.R. 500.306 (Specially Designated Nationals), and authorizes gubernatorial
designation under state law during a declared emergency.
Proposed law authorizes the governor, during a declared state of emergency to suspend,
restrict, refuse performance of, or cancel a state contract if the governor determines that a
beneficiary of the contract is a foreign adversary or foreign terrorist organization and
continuation of the contract poses an unacceptable risk to the security, public health, safety,
economic stability, or emergency preparedness of the state.
Proposed law requires the governor, prior to designation, to consult with the director of the
Governor's Office of Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness and the attorney
